{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fd3f10f8-cff3-457c-9ea9-07f649f43fa1","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but I can tell you exactly what you need to configure to publish a C# MCP server as a `dotnet tool` on NuGet.org:\n\n### In your `.csproj`, add these properties:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName> <!-- CLI command name -->\n  <PackageOutputPath>./nupkg</PackageOutputPath>\n\n  <!-- Required NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points:\n\n1. **`PackAsTool`** — makes it installable via `dotnet tool install`\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the command users type to run it\n3. **`OutputType`** must be `Exe` (should already be for a stdio server)\n\n### Publish workflow:\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push ./nupkg/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server   # runs the stdio MCP server\n```\n\nThat's the minimum configuration. Would you like me to create or update your `.csproj` file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"80b014f6-987f-4827-aa48-9a89c152196e","outputTokens":476,"requestId":"700A:2B88A6:1405838:173E357:69EC11E8"},"id":"893ec278-0256-48fc-800a-f99408331aaf","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:59:29.301Z","parentId":"d7e4ef99-e727-441d-846e-5f16412cecdb"}
